rmk: A little time before recording these calls, I had seen a pair of White-breasted Waterhens with five chicks in foraging in dense shrubs. When I returned to the spot, the family had separated, with one adult on one side of a pathway and the rest of the family on the other side in the same bushes. I assumed that the clucking sounds were made because of me, but then I noticed two feral cats under a car parked near by. The waterhen which has separated from the family was most likely a male, as it was marginally bigger than the other individual, and the black on the back a bit more glossier. The clucking sounds made by the male were occasionally responded by faint clucking sounds by the female.

1. Recording has not been modified.
2. Habitat: The sound was coming from a bamboo bush, it was difficult to reach on the other side of the bush, thus I could not see/photograph the bird. Note that the location is an agriculture field surrounded by trees and bushes.
3. The bird call was loud and continuous, with hardly few seconds gap each minute. It lasted for at least one hour. When the call ended, in the last few minutes the sound changed and became something like a cry (a crying baby to be more precise). I have recording for that too but I am unable to select multiple files to upload.
4. Weather was cloudy, the recording is from early morning (dawn).

An older recording of a White-breasted Waterhen (Uwak) making less commonly heard calls. Many of us would be familiar with the ‘classical’, calls these bird make – a cacophony of loud, raucous notes that are answered by the mate – often sounding like its local name “uwak-wak-wak-wak”. The bird also has larger repertoire of other calls. One that I hear infrequently is the one shown in the video (video here: https://youtu.be/ELHfqhO3Cqo). They are discrete, repetitive calls made every 1.2 seconds (16 calls in 19 seconds) and last 0.2-0.3 of a second. Few authors describe them. Craig Robson (Field Guide to Birds of SE Asia 2002) alludes to them as contact calls and describes them as “pwik”. B

rmk:
Calls of three White-breasted Waterhens along a roadside at Guandu Nature Park in Beitou District, Taipei City.  The waterhens were observed foraging in the exposed mud by a tidal mangrove (?) habitat.  The rails disappeared shortly after spotting them; I used playback to see if I could attract them back into viewing range.  The playback initiated a string a contact calls, as heard on the recording.  The birds continued these calls for several minutes, though never revealing themselves again.

Weather conditions were partly cloudy skies; later a thunderstorm came in from the east.  High humidity, temperatures somewhere in the 28-32°C range.  Habitat was a tidal mangrove(?) habitat; the tide was out, exposing ample mud in which mudskippers and crabs were present in good numbers.  The Waterhens remained on the mudflats, ducking in and out of the mangrove roots before disappearing from view completely.
